To create blackout DB:-
-----------
1)Create a blackout in OEM to ignore the DB maintenance mode alerts for all databases part of maintenance in MOP

host > monitoring > blackout > create > blackout > create > Add(target) > Onhost (search the server name) > search > select the target name of host > select > set the blacout time according the to deployment timings > submit

STOPPING of DB:-
--------------

Stop DB instances running on CPCPLD-4006

Ps -ef|grep pmon
Ps -ef|grep tns
Ps -ef|grep mrp
Df -kh
Check wallet status and sync check
Select name,open_mode,database_role from v$database;
Show pdbs;
 
Note: before shutting down Db, make sure no backup should run
 
Stop listeners :
lsnrctl stop <listener_name>
Stop database :
shut immediate;

Start DB :--
--------
 
Start DB running on CPCPLD-4006 and check database Sync with Primary and perform DB Sanity
Remove all the blackout settings from OEM created in pre-deployment step of all DB’s.


Start database : startup;
Start listeners : lsnrctl start <listener_name>
 
 
Ps -ef|grep pmon
Ps -ef|grep tns
Ps -ef|grep mrp
Df -kh
Check wallet status and sync check
Select name,open_mode,database_role from v$database;
Show pdbs; 

END Blackout :-
-------------

search server name, right click > oracle database > control > end blackout


IF They are physical servers:-

Create a blackout in OEM to ignore the DB maintenance mode alerts for all databases part of maintenance in MOP

1)Start DB:-

Stop database instances on server - DC4C9V 
To stop database
Sudo su – oraasm
$ps -ef|grep d.bin
$crsctl stat res -t
$crsctl check crs
$crsctl stop crs



B) Start database on server DC4C9V and perform DB Sanity and verify the data guard sync
To start database (perform on both nodes)
Sudo su – oraasm
$ps -ef|grep d.bin
$crsctl stat res -t
$crsctl check crs
$crsctl start crs
 
Remove the all blackout settings from OEM created in pre-deployment step of all DB	

